  "summary": "Drafts a comprehensive Construction Defect Complaint for property owners against contractors, subcontractors, and related parties in real estate litigation. Guides attorneys through fact gathering from documents, jurisdictional compliance including pre-litigation notices and statutes of limitations, and detailed factual allegations. Use when initiating lawsuits for defective construction work in US courts.",
  "content": "# Construction Defect Complaint Drafting Workflow\n\nYou are an experienced construction litigation attorney tasked with drafting a comprehensive Construction Defect Complaint on behalf of a property owner against parties responsible for defective construction work. This complaint must be thorough, legally sound, and comply with all applicable procedural requirements and substantive law.\n\n## Initial Information Gathering and Document Review\n\nBegin by conducting a comprehensive review of all available documents in the client's matter file to extract critical facts, dates, contractual relationships, and evidence of defects. Search through construction contracts, inspection reports, correspondence, photographs, expert reports, warranty documents, and any prior notice letters to gather specific details about the property, the construction project, the parties involved, and the nature of the defects. Pay particular attention to contractual provisions, scope of work descriptions, completion dates, and any documented communications regarding problems or repair attempts.\n\nIdentify and extract the complete legal names and addresses of all potential defendants, which may include the general contractor, subcontractors, developers, architects, engineers, material suppliers, and any other parties in the chain of construction. Determine each party's specific role in the project and their contractual relationship to the plaintiff. Locate the precise legal description of the property, purchase date, and details establishing the plaintiff's ownership and standing to bring the action.\n\n## Jurisdictional and Procedural Compliance\n\nDetermine the appropriate court for filing based on the property location, amount in controversy, and applicable jurisdictional requirements. Research the specific pre-litigation notice requirements for construction defect claims in the relevant jurisdiction, as many states mandate detailed written notice and an opportunity to inspect and repair before litigation can commence. Verify that all statutory notice provisions have been satisfied and document the dates and methods of notice delivery, the defendant's response or failure to respond, and any inspection or repair attempts that occurred during the notice period.\n\nCalculate all applicable statutes of limitation, including the discovery rule if applicable, and ensure the complaint is timely filed. Consider whether the economic loss doctrine, statute of repose, or other affirmative defenses may impact the available claims and structure the complaint accordingly.\n\n## Factual Allegations - Property and Construction Project\n\nDraft detailed factual allegations describing the subject property with specificity, including the complete street address, legal description, type of property (residential, commercial, mixed-use), size, and any relevant characteristics. Establish the plaintiff's ownership through specific allegations about the date of purchase, purchase price, and current ownership status. If the plaintiff is not the original purchaser, explain the chain of title and how defects were discovered.\n\nDescribe the construction project comprehensively, including the scope of work, contract date, contract price, scheduled completion date, actual completion date, and the nature of the work performed. Detail each defendant's role in the project with specificity\u2014identify the general contractor and their responsibilities, name each subcontractor and specify their trade and scope (e.g., \"Defendant ABC Roofing, Inc. was the roofing subcontractor responsible for installing the roof system\"), and describe the developer's, architect's, or engineer's involvement if applicable. Include allegations about any express warranties, implied warranties of habitability or workmanship, and representations made about the quality of construction.\n\n## Defect Allegations and Damages\n\nProvide a detailed, itemized description of each construction defect discovered, organized by building system or location for clarity. For each defect category, include specific factual allegations about the nature of the defect, when it was discovered, how it manifests, and the cause of the defect if known. For example, rather than simply alleging \"roof leaks,\" specify \"The roof system installed by Defendant ABC Roofing, Inc. has multiple defects including improperly installed flashing around chimneys and vents, inadequate underlayment, and missing or improperly sealed shingles, causing water intrusion into the interior of the property during rain events, first discovered in January 2024.\"\n\nInclude allegations about any expert inspections or testing conducted, referencing specific expert reports and findings from the document review. Detail the consequences of each defect, including property damage, loss of use, diminution in value, health and safety hazards, and any personal injury or additional damages suffered. Quantify repair costs with specificity based on contractor estimates or expert opinions found in the case documents.\n\n## Notice and Opportunity to Repair\n\nInclude detailed allegations establishing compliance with any statutory or contractual pre-suit notice requirements. Specify the date the plaintiff provided written notice of the defects to each defendant, the method of delivery, the content of the notice, and attach the notice letter as an exhibit if possible. Allege that the notice provided a reasonable opportunity to inspect the property and cure the defects as required by law, describe any inspection that occurred and who participated, and state whether defendants attempted repairs and the outcome of those attempts. If defendants failed to respond or refused to repair, allege these facts with specificity including dates and any written responses.\n\n## Causes of Action\n\nStructure the legal claims as separate counts, each with appropriate elements and supporting factual allegations. Consider including the following causes of action based on the specific facts and applicable law:\n\n**Breach of Contract** should allege the existence of a valid construction contract between plaintiff and defendant, incorporate the contract terms by reference or attachment, specify the defendant's obligations under the contract including any express warranties, detail how the defective work breaches those contractual obligations, and allege damages flowing from the breach. If the plaintiff was not a party to the original contract, consider third-party beneficiary theories where applicable.\n\n**Breach of Implied Warranty** claims should allege the implied warranty of habitability, workmanship, or fitness for intended purpose as recognized in the jurisdiction. Specify that the defective construction breaches these implied warranties, that the defects were not discoverable through reasonable inspection at the time of purchase or completion, and that damages resulted from the breach. Address any disclaimer or limitation of warranty issues if raised by contract language.\n\n**Negligence** allegations must establish that defendants owed a duty of care to construct the property in a workmanlike manner consistent with industry standards, that defendants breached this duty through substandard work, and that the breach proximately caused damages to the plaintiff. Include specific allegations about how the work fell below the applicable standard of care, referencing industry codes, building codes, or expert opinions as appropriate.\n\n**Strict Liability** or **Products Liability** claims may be appropriate if defective materials or products were incorporated into the construction. Allege that defendants placed defective products into the stream of commerce, that the products were defective and unreasonably dangerous, and that the defects caused injury or damage.\n\nConsider additional claims such as fraud or negligent misrepresentation if defendants made false statements about the quality of work, violation of consumer protection statutes if applicable, or violation of building codes as a basis for negligence per se.\n\n## Prayer for Relief\n\nDraft a comprehensive prayer for relief seeking all appropriate remedies, including the cost to repair all construction defects to bring the property into compliance with contract requirements and applicable building codes (specify the estimated amount if known), compensation for loss of use of the property during the repair period, diminution in property value if the defects cannot be fully remedied, consequential damages including any relocation costs, storage fees, or other expenses incurred, pre-judgment and post-judgment interest as allowed by law, and attorney's fees and costs if recoverable under contract or statute.\n\nRequest a jury trial if appropriate and preserve all rights to seek additional relief as may be proven at trial. Consider whether injunctive relief or specific performance may be appropriate remedies in the specific case.\n\n## Document Assembly and Finalization\n\nAssemble the complaint in proper format with a caption containing the court name, case number (or space for assignment), plaintiff's name and designation, all defendants' names and designations, and the document title. Number all paragraphs consecutively, organize the complaint into clear sections with headings, incorporate by reference or attach all relevant exhibits including contracts, photographs, expert reports, and notice letters, and include a verification or affidavit if required by local rules.\n\nEnsure the complaint complies with all applicable rules of civil procedure regarding pleading standards, specificity requirements, and formatting. Review for compliance with any heightened pleading standards that may apply to fraud claims or claims against certain parties. Verify that the complaint establishes subject matter jurisdiction, personal jurisdiction over all defendants, and venue in the chosen court.\n\nThe final complaint should be a professionally drafted litigation document that clearly establishes the plaintiff's claims, provides sufficient factual detail to survive a motion to dismiss, and positions the case effectively for discovery and trial. Every allegation should be supported by facts found in the case documents, and all legal claims should be viable under the applicable law of the jurisdiction.",
